      <h1 class="why-title">Why I Built This</h1>

      <div class="why-body">

        <p>You enjoy art. You may even have a mild fascination with the art world, its prices, its mysteries. The who's who. Or, you make art. Maybe you've been at it for years. Maybe you just started. Either way—whether you're drawn to art or driven to make it—there's a niggling incompletion that doesn't go away. You're almost getting something—in the gallery, in your own work—but comfortable closure keeps just slipping out of reach.</p>

        <p>It shows up differently for different people. Here's one: You came home from the coast with sixty photographs and a head full of weather.</p>

        <p>The storm had been extraordinary—wind you could lean into, waves hitting the rocks and throwing spray twenty feet into the air, that particular gray-green the ocean turns when the sky closes down. You stood there and felt genuinely changed. You needed to paint it.</p>

        <p>So you set up in your studio and worked from the photographs. You made something that looked like waves and sky. Something that, if someone asked what it was, you could say "it's the coast during a storm" and they'd agree. But it wasn't the thing. The awe wasn't in it. Whatever had changed you out there on the rocks wouldn't cross over onto the canvas.</p>

        <p>You brought the work to your monthly group. Everyone was kind. They had suggestions—different palette, looser brushwork, maybe the composition. You tried those things. None of them fixed it.</p>

        <p>More time in the studio wouldn't have fixed this. The problem wasn't how well you could handle a brush—you could handle a brush. The problem was that nobody had ever shown you how to take what you felt on those rocks and build it into something a viewer can actually feel.</p>

        <p>I know this because the same gap shows up everywhere. It shows up in a working artist's studio three months before a major gallery show, staring at ten canvases that won't do what they should do. It shows up in the MFA critique room when a student can execute anything and still can't locate what they're actually trying to say. It shows up in front of a Rothko at the museum when an intelligent person stands there feeling like they're supposed to be getting something they can't reach. Different stages, different vocabularies for the frustration—but the same structural problem underneath: something you experienced or know or feel won't cross the threshold into the work.</p>

        <p>My version of that gap looked like this.</p>

        <p>I came to art through a darkroom. Commercial printing, large-format cameras, color separations—I learned the physics of color before I understood why color mattered. Dot frequency, optical mixture, what happens when two wavelengths land adjacent on a retina. I understood the substrate before I understood the content.</p>

        <p>When I went to art school, I walked into a world organized around ideas I couldn't name. Fine art in service of ideas—that was the water everyone swam in. Nobody explained it because they didn't think they needed to. The right people would just know. I didn't know. The door was there. The key wasn't offered. I walked out with craft—real craft—but couldn't find my footing in a conversation I'd never been given the language for.</p>

        <p>What followed was two and a half decades of commercial work: Pabst Blue Ribbon, Harry &amp; David, Wolferman's, PetSmart, Breyers Ice Cream, Lone Star Beer. Work that had to earn attention in two seconds of shelf time, under bad lighting, against a wall of competition. Either the structure held or it didn't. That world gave me something art school hadn't: a hard test with immediate results.</p>

        <p>The better I got at passing it, the clearer something became. The whole job was to stop a stranger for two seconds and hand their attention to a brand—make them reach, make them remember, make them come back. Everything the design did was in service of that transfer. That was the job, and redirection was the right tool for it. I was good at it. But the same move fails in fine art—and not just when the target is a product. Even when attention gets redirected toward an idea, a concept, an artist's declared position, the viewer ends up somewhere other than their own experience. What I wanted to make was work that didn't redirect at all. That activated something the viewer could feel in the body before they knew what to think about it.</p>

        <p>That sent me back to painting. And this time I had something I hadn't had before—not just craft, but a question worth working on. Not trying to express something. Not trying to serve a product. Trying to build conditions—the kind of visual structure that doesn't tell you what to feel, but makes feeling possible. Where the viewer does the real work, and the painting makes that work available.</p>

        <p>Years later I became a museum docent. Not to teach—I had no intention of teaching anyone anything. I love art museums the way some people love cathedrals: as preserves. Places where the original works actually live, where you can stand in front of the real thing and let it act on you. I'd traveled to other cities, other countries, just to see originals that had shaped my practice. Being in front of the actual object—not a reproduction, not a screen—is physical for me. A genuine thrill that kept making me want more.</p>

        <p>The Schneider Museum felt like a chance to go deeper into that world. I was a complete neophyte. I had no idea how any of it worked from the inside. Underneath the curiosity was a quieter question I couldn't quite name yet: would what I knew transfer here? It was, if I'm honest, entirely about me.</p>

        <p>And here's where it gets complicated. On my last docent tour, someone stood in front of a sculpture—leaning in, genuinely trying—and then said, reluctantly, almost apologetically: "I'm just not getting it." I didn't reach for an explanation. I shrugged and said quietly, "I understand." They seemed visibly relieved. Not because I'd fixed anything. Because someone had finally just recognized where they were.</p>

        <p>It was the exact feeling I'd had at art school thirty years earlier. And I kept finding it everywhere. Smart, curious people in front of serious work, with no entry point. Left outside the same door.</p>

        <p>Not a talent problem. A structural one.</p>

        <p>The thing I eventually understood—and it took most of a career—is that the gap isn't closed by more practice, stronger emotion, or better technique. It's closed by understanding the visual structure that connects experience to image. Not rules. Mechanisms. The physics of what actually happens when light, shape, and color land on a human visual system. The structure that operates before the viewer—or the painter—decides what to think about it.</p>

        <p>Most of us were never taught this. Not in workshops, not in books about famous painters, not in years of monthly group critique. We were taught style, history, the vocabulary of movements. We were taught to look at finished work and evaluate it. Nobody taught us how the structure of a painting acts on a body in real time.</p>

        <p>That's what Art Lab is built to do. Not tell you what your work should mean—that's always yours. But give you the tools to close the gap. Between the storm you stood in and the painting you're trying to make. Between what you felt on those rocks and what you can get onto the canvas.</p>

        <p>The gap isn't about talent. It's about being able to see what's already working—and knowing what to reach for when it isn't.</p>

      </div>

